eden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1144–Male":"1144–Overleden","1148–Male":"1148–Overleden","1155–1197":"1155–1197","1080–1115":"1080–1115","1080":"1080","1139":"1139","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","about 1115":"circa 1115","1197":"1197","1140":"1140","after 1166":"na 1166","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England":"Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1115–after 1166":"about 1115–after 1166","1110–1197":"1110–1197","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1139–Male":"1139–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1144–Male":"1144–Deceased","1148–Male":"1148–Deceased","1155–1197":"1155–1197","1080–1115":"1080–1115","1080":"1080","1139":"1139","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","about 1115":"about 1115","1197":"1197","1140":"1140","after 1166":"after 1166","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England":"Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Verdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Renaud, Sylvie.","French: habitational name from (Le) Verdon, the name of several places in various parts of France, for example in Dordogne, Gironde, and Marne. Compare   Ferdon  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Verdun, the name of a fief in Vessey (Manche), France. Compare   Verdun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Verdin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ramon, Angel, Luis, Ruben, Azael, Fernando, Fidel, Francisco, Guillermo, Javier.","English (Lancashire and Cheshire): variant of   Verdon  .","Altered form of French   Verdun  ."]},{"name":"Ferdon","meanings":["Altered form, under American Dutch influence in New Netherland, of French   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Wearden","meanings":["English (Lancashire): apparently from a placename with Old English <i>denu</i> ‘valley’ as the second element. However, the Victoria County History for Staffordshire identifies John <i>de Werdon</i>, mentioned in 1280, as having his name from Verdun (Manche, France); see   Verdon  ."]},{"name":"Verdun","meanings":["French: habitational name from any of several places in France called Verdun. The placename is probably of Gaulish origin, deriving from <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, fortress’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from Verdú in Catalonia (Spain), which has the same origin as the French name (see 1 above).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Verdon  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is very rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Verdon was born about 1115, in Saxlingham, Norfolk, England as the son of Ives de Verdon. He had at least 6 sons. He died after 1166, in Aslacton, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"about 1115–after 1166":"umbes 1115–pärast 1166","1110–1197":"1110–1197","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1139–Male":"1139–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1144–Male":"1144–Surnud","1148–Male":"1148–Surnud","1155–1197":"1155–1197","1080–1115":"1080–1115","1080":"1080","1139":"1139","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","about 1115":"umbes 1115","1197":"1197","1140":"1140","after 1166":"pärast 1166","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England":"Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1115–after 1166":"noin 1115–1166 jälkeen","1110–1197":"1110–1197","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1139–Male":"1139–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1144–Male":"1144–Kuollut","1148–Male":"1148–Kuollut","1155–1197":"1155–1197","1080–1115":"1080–1115","1080":"1080","1139":"1139","1115":"1115","1148":"1148","1155":"1155","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","about 1115":"noin 1115","1197":"1197","1140":"1140","after 1166":"1166 jälkeen","Aslacton, Norfolk, England":"Aslacton, Norfolk, England","Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England":"Moulton St Mary, Norfolk, England","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1115–after 1166":"environ 1115–après 1166","1110–1197":"1110–1197","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1139–Male":"1139–Décédé","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1144–Male":"1144–Décédé","1148–